column69: Naples, parking lot Berkshire Commons
column153: Saw a large green lizard sunning himself in the parkinglot. He wasn't traditional iguana but he had large claws. His eyes were very round and large. I would not have even noticed him at all but he charged at me. I have owned reptiles as pets before but this lizard was aggressive! I tried looking him up online and I suspect he may be a Cuban Knight Anole but I don't know much about them. I could tell whatever he is, he was not fully grown. His coloring didn't match pictures of any of the adult invasives I looked up online. It concerns me because a friend of mine gave an identical description of this type of lizard in Cambier Park in Naples two days after I saw one. (And Cambier Park is a good 5 miles from where I saw this one!) I did not think to grab a picture but she did take a picture and it is the exact same type of lizard. I had another friend see one off of Pineridge Road and Napa Boulevard. So, they are in more than one place in Naples.

column153: Private residence at 385 Pompano Drive. Knight anole was first observed and captured 30 minutes later on south side of house, having moved approximately 20 feet higher into tree canopy. UTM location: 17R 0560926 m E, 2780473 m N with error shown as +/- 2m. Also shifted position format to Lat./Long. and estimated anole was two meters south of N 25.13899 x W 080.39555 with error shown as +/- 2m (w/ elevation taken from roof at capture site shown on Garmin eTrex 10 as 13 meters) using GPS + GLONASS. Observed a young "knight anole" (Anolis equestris) as it climbed a gumbo limbo tree from appproximately 10 feet above ground into tree canopy at approximately 30 feet above ground. I left it for fifteen minutes to assemble suitable equipment for attempting a live capture. Then, after taking several photos (attached) I captured it from our third-floor balcony, using a noose pole made from a twelve-foot long surf rod with braided dacron leader as a noose.
